Introduction:

Global development is a complicated subject, particularly because there is no one form of development. Any given nation could develop in a wide variety of ways as certain elements of development are given preference to others. One important concept is the effect of positive externalities in development that lead to development in one area having a positive impact on other aspects of development. For this reason, many aspects of global development influence one another and measuring a nations development patterns cannot be done by looking at a single developmental metric. It also makes measuring development in specific areas particularly complicated.

The Human Rights Measurement Initiative (HRMI) attempts to summarize the human rights performance of over 200 nations over a variety of economic, social, civil, and political rights. In addition to standard socioeconomic data such as GDP per capita and survival rate by age group, HRMI provides scores to a wide variety of different data based on current outcomes in that category versus what is economically feasible given the nations resources. These scores range from 0 to 100, with low scores indicating poor performance and high scores indicating high performance. It is important to note that some nations do not have consistent data across all variables and some do not have certain data whatsoever. The inconsistent data collection methods common in developing nations and the low incentive to publish human rights information found in nations committing human rights violations means that there are many unavailable data in the data set. Also important to note is that not all variables in the data set are relevant to all nations. For example, Net Secondary School Enrolment is relevant to high-income nations but not low-and-middle-income nations. More details regarding how the data is organized can be found in a PDF with the .zip file containing the current data set.

This project will use the current HRMI data set to explore how very different kinds of development may be related to one another in developing regions. Specifically, this project will explore the relationship between access to education and sanitation as described in the ESR_LMY_IncomeAdjusted subset of data. It is plausible that these to forms of development are correlated with one another because sanitation may serve as a barrier to education and education access could improve sanitation development. If the data are strongly correlated, then it may be possible to predict some of the missing data. The hypothesis statement is as follows:

##Among low-and-middle-income nations, there is a strong correlation between primary school enrollment and access to basic sanitation. A linear regression model can be created using these data that can provide rough estimates for missing data.

Data Analysis:

The project begins with filtering data types. It is concerned with low-and-middle-income nations (LMY) data. This project also examines their primary education data and their basic sanitation data, which are applicable to the ESR_LMY_IncomeAdjusted data set but not the high-income ESR_HIY_IncomeAdjusted (HiY) data set. It will conclude with suggestions regarding the usefulness of applying the same method to other nation groups or data types.

The primary school data is more frequently missing due to entire nations being excluded from this data type. Some missing data are due to data missing from specific years, such as Iraq missing data from 2018. However, many are due to data likely being withheld or not collected whatsoever. These nations do not have data for any of the years in the given period. For example, North Korea and China do not have this data for any year.

By contrast, most of the instances of missing data regarding Basic Sanitation are due to unavailability of specific years, like American Samoa and Cuba only missing this data for the year 2018. Kosovo is the only nation to lack this data completely, which is likely due to Kosovos contested statehood and declaration of independence in 2008.

Because of this, it is sensible to filter out missing data from both variables completely.Setting null values to zero for Primary School data is not reasonable, as the lack of data is often due to data withheld instead of lack of infrastructure.

No.NA.Primary.School<-filter(simplified.LMY.Data, is.na(simplified.LMY.Data$Net_Primary_School_Enrollment)=="FALSE")

filter(No.NA.Primary.School, is.na(No.NA.Primary.School$Basic_Sanitation)=="TRUE")
##   Country Year Net_Primary_School_Enrollment Basic_Sanitation
## 1    Cuba 2018                         97.74               NA
## 2 Eritrea 2017                         51.75               NA
## 3 Eritrea 2018                         51.46               NA

After null values in the primary school data are filtered out, the null values for basic sanitation can also be filtered out. The output above shows that only 3 rows have been filtered out. The data filtered out are Cuba 2018, Eritrea 2017, and Eritrea 2018. This shows that most nations lacking primary school data already lack basic sanitation data, so adding an additional filter has made the data slightly cleaner without excluding much. A linear model suggests a very strong relationship between the two variables. The F-statistic is 549.6 while the p-value is much lower than the standard level of significance of .05. If there is truly a meaningful relationship between the two variables, it follows that the data would roughly follow a line of best fit. The next section will display the data via scatterplot and histograms to see if this is true.

For the following scatterplots, PE is short for Net_Primary_School_Enrollment and BS is short for Basic_Sanitation.

#Scatterplots and Histograms of Data

plot(Net_Primary_School_Enrollment~Basic_Sanitation, data = Filtered.LMY.Data, main = "PE vs BS Across LMY Nations")
abline(Filtered.Plot.Line, col="red") 

hist(Filtered.LMY.Data$Net_Primary_School_Enrollment, breaks = 10)

hist(Filtered.LMY.Data$Basic_Sanitation, breaks = 10)

Looking at the scatterplot, it is clear that the data is very heavily skewed in favor of data with high basic sanitation and high primary education enrollment. This skew is clearly demonstrated by the odd line of best fit, which only intersects the dense cluster of data points in the top right corner of the graph.

A histogram of both variables shows that the data is definitely not normally distributed, meaning t-testing and ANOVA testing are not helpful here. Further, both variables demonstrate a leftward skew and the skew is much more pronounced for primary school enrollment. Because the relationship between basic sanitation and primary school enrollment appears so different at lower levels, it is feasible that filtering below the skew of Net_Primary_School_Enrollment and repeating the regression analysis would demonstrate the extent to which this relationship holds. In other words, different levels of development would demonstrate different patterns within these variables.

Three filtering options are available.The first is to filter for results below the median (90.98). The second is to filter below the mean (86.8053713). The third is to filter based on official development classifications published by the World Bank on the assumption that development level indicates different patterns. Because of the heavy skew in the data, the mean will be used to re-filter data.

#Filtering for Below Average PE Scores

Low.Primary.Enrollment<-filter(Filtered.LMY.Data, Filtered.LMY.Data$Net_Primary_School_Enrollment<mean(Filtered.LMY.Data$Net_Primary_School_Enrollment))
Low.Primary.Enrollment.Line<-lm(Net_Primary_School_Enrollment~Basic_Sanitation, data=Low.Primary.Enrollment)
plot(Net_Primary_School_Enrollment~Basic_Sanitation, data=Low.Primary.Enrollment, main = "PE vs BS among Nations with Below Average PE Scores")
abline(Low.Primary.Enrollment.Line, col="red")

The new scatterplot seems to show a much weaker relationship and the regression line is much less predictive of Basic_Sanitation. Next are the summary statistics of the regression.

## Multiple R-squared:  0.1411, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1393 
## F-statistic:  75.6 on 1 and 460 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Statistically speaking, there is still a strong relation between Basic_Sanitation and Net_Primary_School_Enrollment due to the F-statistic being above 75.6 and p-value being far below .05. Interestingly, no data points are located in the bottom-right corner of the scatterplot, while many are located in the top-left corner. This suggests that improved basic sanitation scores contribute to higher primary school enrollment, while higher primary school enrollment does not contribute to higher sanitation. Plotting and performing a regression of above average PE scores will enable analyzing the clustered area further.

How useful are these estimates? Note that the average PE score across LMY nations not missing PE data is 86.7641898. For nations like Rwanda, this may be close enough. However, none of the nations PE estimates fall below this average and some, like Iraq and Tokelau, are considerably higher and data from other years suggests this estimate is more accurate.

For most of these data, using the average PE value as a substitute for null values instead of a regression estimate would likely underestimate educational enrollment at the higher end of the distribution. This is typical when substituting null values with an average. However, the analysis shows how doing so can be misleading when used in a human rights or development context. The wide variety of different kinds of development which exist and the different statistical patterns which are exhibited at different places in the development spectrum mean that estimation using the average of an immensely complex gamut of international trends is unrealistic. Doing so may even be harmful given the human rights and developmental implications. Moreover, having nation-specific estimates of economic development patterns is more helpful because a considerable amount of human rights and development analysis is nation-specific or regional instead of global.

Is this strategy feasible for other data and socioeconomic strata? Next, this analysis will repeat the filtering and regression process for the high-income nation (HiY) dataset. The Net Secondary School Enrolment and People with at least safely managed sanitation data will be used to analyze high-income nations, as these data are specific to high-income nations and are comparable to the data used in the LMY analysis. Instead of excluding results based on average, data above the average for sanitation are colored light blue and a regression of all nations in the dataframe is performed.

## Multiple R-squared:  0.04523,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.04333 
## F-statistic: 23.83 on 1 and 503 DF,  p-value: 1.418e-06

After repeating the data filtering, plotting, and regression analysis steps used in the LMY data set, some important commonalities and differences can be observed. First is that the histograms are similarly skewed to the left. Second is the clustering in the top-right corner of the scatterplot, indicating a relationship between high sanitation and high educational enrollment. However, the corresponding F-score is much lower at 23.83 and some significant outliers can be seen. While the F-score and p-value both suggest a statistically significant relationship between the Safely_Managed_Sanitation and Net_Secondary_School_Enrollment data, this relationship only demonstrates some of the patterns of the previous analysis.

What does this mean? The differences between the LMY and HiY analyses may be partly due to the differences in data used. While similar, there may be numerous statistically-meaningful differences between primary and secondary school enrollment which lead to different data trends. However, it is also apparent that different developmental patterns occur at different stages of development. Primary school enrollment may be challenging to predict at low levels of basic sanitation development but easier to develop at higher ones. Sanitation as a predictor variable may become less useful once again at high income levels due to nations achieving more complicated bureaucracy and institutions which may also contribute to developmental patterns. It is also possible that, since developed nations generally have strong sanitation and rarely fall below 60 in safe sanitation management (visible in the scatterplot), sanitation is not a meaningful predictor and another variable might better predict secondary school enrollment.

Conclusion:

The desire for quick and easy assessment strategies is common in global development and human rights. Unfortunately, gaps in data availability make assessing a nations developmental standing difficult in many cases.As this analysis has shown, assigning average values to missing data can misrepresent a nations current developmental standing. This is particularly unhelpful for local developers and policymakers who work with specific nations and not the entire globe. There is an opportunity to use regression analysis to develop linear models capable of approximating some of these null values. However, doing so requires a careful understanding of the data and thorough data analysis. Further, regression methods which are effective among certain nations or with specific variables may not be effective in other contexts. As development work continues, developmental organizations and peacebuilders will need to remember that there are no panacea in this field.
